But 68 per cent said they like receiving hand written letters in the post and a further six in ten admitted they get excited when they receive a gift in the mail.

Mark Walters, managing director of Interparcel, said: 'In a fast-moving modern world it's easy to forget to stop and appreciate certain things as fully as the generations before us did.

'Our homes are sleeker, our technology is increasingly compact and as a result the heirlooms or things that may have emotional value can seem out of place or ill-fitting.

'Results showed people are quicker to throw things out than perhaps they used to be and many don't feel as sentimental about things as they did.

'Whether it's sending a thoughtful gift, a handwritten note or a postcard, keeping that personal touch in day to day life is important.'

